Inheritance¶

  • In Short: Deriving class from an existing class

Inheritance Philosophy¶

We achiece reusability in out code, by borrowing features from parent child, into child class

class Rectangle{}

class Cuboid: public Rectangle{}

All data members and functions from Base class are shared by the "child" or Derived class

The Derived class access to Base class's member* is only limited by Access Specifiers (more about this later)

Thats is :

private 
protected
public

The flow of calls (not execution) always starts at Base Class, then to Derived Class, where execution occurs. (more about this later)

Cnstructors¶

class Base{
public: 
    Base(){
        cout<<"Default Base"<<endl;
    }

    Base(int x){
        cout<<"Parameterized Base "<<x<<endl;
    }

}

class Derived: Base{
public: 
    Derived(){
        cout<<"Default Derived"<<endl;
    }

    Derived(int y){
        cout<<"Parameterized Derived "<<y<<endl;
    }

}

As indicated flow goes from parent to child, that means first the Base Constructor is called, then the Derived Constructor

[OUTPUT]

Derived d;

Default Base
Default Derived

How does the parameterised of Derived will work. First the Default of Base is called, then Param of Derived is called

[OUTPUT]

Derived D(10);

Default Base
Parameterized Derived 10

So for (when called) Default and Param of Derived, The Defualt Constructer in both cases will be exucuted first.

But what is I want the Param of Base (not Default Base) to be called, when Param of Derived is called? How is this achieved?

We need a special constructor for Derived: How do we read it?

We pass two arguments, one for base (x), other is for Derived(y).

But how do we get x to Base? we write, :Base (x)

Derived (int x, int y) : Base (x){
        cout<<"Param of  Derived "<<y<<endl;
    }
}

[OUTPUT]

Parameterized Base 10
Param of  Derived 20

Now the param of Base is called first, value (x) gotton from Derived,then Param of Derived is called.

That is Param Base is called from Param Derived.

Is-a and has-a¶

Is-a is used for Parent-child relationship where you have a Base and Derived Class

Has-a is used where you using one class inside another

These are the two ways a class can be used:

  1. Derived from another class(Parent-child) (is-a)
  2. Having an object of one class, inside another (has-a)

Access Specifiers¶

We have the following Access Specifiers:

private 
protected
public
class Base{
private:
  int a;      
protected:
  int b;        
public: 
  int c;  

  void funBase(){
        a=10;
        b=20;
        c=30;
    }
}

[OUTPUT]

Base x;
x.a=10;  [Not possible]
x.b=20;  [Not possible]
x.c=30;  [Possible]

But the access specifiers become more complex, when you dealing wih Parent-Child (Inherited) Classes.

Here are the RULES (easy):

  1. Outside the class, only public members are accessible
  2. Inherited classes: protected and public is accessible between parent and child

Heree are the RULES (hard): Given: private is ONLY accessible to class itself

  1. public Parent (this is default one)

From Parent to Child: protected becomes proctected public becomes public

From Child to Grandchild: Grandchild have access to parent and child (protected and public)

  1. protected Parent

From Parent to Child: protected becomes proctected public becomes protected

From Child to Grandchild: Grandchild still have access to parent and child (protected and public)

  1. private Parent

From Parent to Child: protected becomes private public becomes private

From Child to Grandchild: Grandchild has NO ACCESS to parent (GrandParent)

Types of Inheritance¶

Single/Simple Class inherits from single class

Herarchical More than one class is inheriting from one class Here the parent class is a general(ised) class

Multilevel Inherit from one class through intermediate class

Multiple Class can inherit from more than one class

Hybrid (Missing Hieratchical and Multiple)

D inherits from A through B and C

The features of Base Class A will be appearing in D, via A and via C

This is called Multipart Inheritance, D gets copy of A, via B or via C. Which is the correct one...i.e. But this is a problem (ambiguity).

To remove this ambiguity, we have concept of virtual base classes

class A{}

class B: virtual public A

class C: virtual public A

class D: public B, public C
